title.children: How the deadly shooting at Donald Trump's rally unfolded

image.altText: The silhouette of a man in uniform can be seen behind a window with a sign on it that says KGB on it

props.synopsis: Russia's extensive and secretive intelligence networks extend around the world, but after its invasion of Ukraine, the nuclear-armed nation has been forced to make strategic changes to the way it spies abroad, as Australia found out this week.

title.children: 'Russia will use any means it can': Inside Putin's 'paranoid' spy network

image.altText: Two firefighters spray water into a window, while a man in a grey shirt points up at it.

props.synopsis: The Israeli army targets Hamas military chief Mohammed Deif in Khan Younis, killing dozens of Palestinians.

title.children: At least 90 Palestinians reportedly killed in Israeli air strike targeting Hamas military chief

image.altText: A bulldozer removes a section of building

props.synopsis: For decades, thousands of people thought they were buying land and built their homes there. But the title holder was always a superannuation company, and now it has brought in the bulldozers.

title.children: Satellite images show how a whole community has been illegally built. Now bulldozers are moving in

image.altText: Sheets of lead among other products with their prices on a Bunnings store shelf next to a helmet.

props.synopsis: Work safety authorities in at least three states called into the hardware giant, amid fears customers and workers have been put at risk by inappropriate handling of the potentially hazardous material.

title.children: Lead exposure concerns forces Bunnings to change product packaging

image.altText: A digital render of a skeleton.

props.synopsis: Investigators used a new technique to identify 95-year-old human remains found in the water at Sandy Point in Gippsland. The forensic breakthrough has raised hopes that more cold cases could soon be solved.

title.children: A new technique helped solve the Sandy Point mystery — investigators now have more unsolved cases in their sights

image.altText: Richard Simmons

props.synopsis: American fitness guru Richard Simmons has died aged 76.

title.children: Richard Simmons, American fitness guru, dies aged 76

image.altText: Jordan Thompson and Max Purcell sit in their chairs after losing Wimbledon men's final.

props.synopsis: Three times, Max Purcell and Jordan Thompson were only a point away from winning the men's doubles crown, but Harri Heliövaara and Henry Patten prevailed in a dramatic final.

title.children: 'It just sucks': Aussie duo lose Wimbledon doubles final after coughing up three championship points

image.altText: frost blankets the roadside in Needles, Tasmania

props.synopsis: Despite the varying climate, the capitals – outside of Darwin – all have one thing in common. They've just shivered through what is historically their coldest week on the calendar. So does it mean the worst of the cold weather is now over?

title.children: It's not your imagination, while the days are getting longer this is why it's the coldest time of year

image.altText: a girl with purple hair wearing an orange jumper is making coffee, there are skateboards on the walls

props.synopsis: What started in the central Victorian town of Seymour as a youth group offering skating lessons and a safe place for young people has grown into a full social enterprise, with plans to expand across Australia.

title.children: In this country town, gnarly skateboarders make for great neighbours

image.altText: A woman and two men supervised over a row of buildings.

props.synopsis: Many people with disability are frustrated with the $1.2 billion program that's supposed to help them find jobs. Now it's getting an overhaul.

title.children: Lachlan lives with disability. He says the meetings he must attend to get support are 'degrading'

image.altText: view of man from behind sitting at studio mixing desk with screen above him with animation on it

props.synopsis: Would you choose to listen to music that's been made by a computer? Screen music composers say they risk being pushed out of their industry without better regulations around the use of artificial intelligence in sound generation.

title.children: How screen composers are fighting to protect their craft against AI that creates songs in seconds

image.altText: A composite image of two men imposed in front of a black and white explosion.

props.synopsis: The discovery by Griffith University scientists has given hope to Gulf War veterans that their often-debilitating symptoms will finally be recognised by the medical profession and the Australian government.

title.children: Ian coughed up 'mucous that tasted like smoke' ever since he served in the Gulf War. He might finally know why

image.altText: An older man wearing a red tie, white shirt and a black suit jacket with a serious expression

props.synopsis: People who worked with Donald Trump are speaking to Four Corners as he makes a bid for his second coming as US president.

title.children: White House insiders who witnessed Trump's extraordinary presidency are speaking out

image.altText: Man with sunglasses on flanked by young woman and older woman

props.synopsis: A father and son have died in a fire at the home in Melbourne's east. Police say the fire is not suspicious.

title.children: House fire leaves father and son dead in Melbourne's east

image.altText: Joel Hill, with bald head and black t-shirt, smiles sitting at wooden table with grass and green bushes behind him.

props.synopsis: Four former conspiracy theorists held beliefs that governed almost every aspect of their lives. Then, for each of them, a powerful trigger made them change their minds. Their stories offer insight into life inside the rabbit hole — and hope for escaping it.

title.children: Joel was a conspiracy theorist who believed medicine was evil. Then his sister needed it to stay alive

image.altText: Two soccer players wearing light blue jerseys high five each other with two players wearing red and white in the background

props.synopsis: With the Paris Olympics just around the corner, the Matildas have lost their final warm-up friendly 2-1 to defending gold medallists Canada.

title.children: Matildas fall 2-1 to Canada in final friendly before Paris Olympics

image.altText: Joe Biden speaks at a news conference in front of two US flags.

props.synopsis: US President Joe Biden has made a series of unfortunate name mistakes in the past week, including introducing Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy as "President Putin". Brain scientists say referring to someone by the wrong name is a common mental slip due to the way our memory is categorised.

title.children: We asked a neuroscientist their thoughts of Joe Biden. They said his slip-ups don't mean cognitive decline

image.altText: A golden dingo looking towards the camera with its tongue out, surrounded by shrubs and grasses.

props.synopsis: Traditional owner and fourth-generation grazier Joshua Henry was raised to see dingoes as a threat to cattle. Now his views have changed and he's adding his voice to calls to ban the killing of dingoes.

title.children: 'Invasive animal' or 'sacred native'? The fight to save the dingo is heating up

image.altText: Kira Korolev stands outside the war memorial in Canberra

props.synopsis: Australia's spy agency ASIO was the first authority to investigate concerns about Russian-born Australian citizen Kira Korolev. What followed was close monitoring of the army private and her husband, which has now landed them in custody, facing allegations of spying for their mother country.

title.children: Kira Korolev, accused of being a Russian spy, didn't shirk spotlight as social media influencer

image.altText: Bushra Bibi sits next to Imran Khan who are both behind a table surrounded by people at a press conference

props.synopsis: The couple were sentenced to seven years in prison in February when a court found them guilty of breaking Islamic law.

title.children: Former Pakistan PM Imran Khan and his wife acquitted of illegal marriage charges

image.altText: John Setka sitting behind a number of microphones at a Melbourne media conference.

props.synopsis: Nine newspapers are alleging underworld figures have been given high-paid roles within the Victorian branch of the construction union.

title.children: Serious allegations against the CFMEU a day after construction union boss Setka quits

image.altText: The  Clifton Suspension Bridge

props.synopsis: A man has been arrested in England after human remains were found inside two suitcases and further human remains discovered at a property in London.

title.children: Man arrested in UK after human remains found in dumped suitcases

image.altText: Firefighter outside burnt house

props.synopsis: Police are investigating a suspicious house fire in Townsville that killed two 18-year-old men.

title.children: Two 18-year-old men dead after fire in Townsville

image.altText: A gaunt man in brown prison garb stares straight ahead at the camera

props.synopsis: Hamza Elbaf has been shut off from the outside world for the past five years. The Australian citizen doesn't even know who the prime minister is. He's one of thousands of suspected ISIS fighters being held in Syrian prisons.

title.children: What was this rugby league fan from the suburbs doing with ISIS?

image.altText: A woman drives a tractor during a tobacco harvest

props.synopsis: A fortnightly gathering over the past four decades has slowly rolled these former tobacco farmers — once isolated, a world away from their Italian homes — into a family.

title.children: From chasing thieves to working 16-hour days, former tobacco farmers have rich memories of life on the land
